    "remarks": {
      "sha256": "231bea990b1029fe06671f62c37b0ede5dd1cd534428bf9d788349e79a02bab4",
      "source_region": "div.problem-additional-text",
      "text": "Erd\\H{o}s and Graham could show this is true (assuming the prime $k$-tuple conjecture) if we replace $\\liminf$ by $\\limsup$."
    },
    "statement": {
      "sha256": "8c49bdda84c0b3737a4ee25b7f882e539980330208ed3924db82f6afcf7239b0",
      "source_region": "div#content",
      "text": "Is there a set $A\\subseteq \\mathbb{N}$ such that, for infinitely many $n$, all of $n-a$ are prime for all $a\\in A$ with $0<a<n$ and\\[\\liminf\\frac{\\lvert A\\cap [1,x]\\rvert}{\\pi(x)}>0?\\]"
    }
  },
